MBT06 Analysis

MBT06 - Shannon Diversity

cols <- grep("MBT06",names(s),value=T);
grps <- factor(gsub("MBT06_|_R[1234]$","",cols),levels=c("INVITRO_P0","INVITRO_CON","INVITRO_R","INVIVO_P0","ENG","MRD_CON","MRD_R","MRD_T","MRD_TR","MRD_TRA","REC_CON","REC_R","REC_T","REC_TR","REC_TRA"));
sums <- apply( co.2[,cols] > 0,2,sum );
maxes <- apply( co.2[,cols],2,max );

df <- data.frame( Diversity=s[cols],Groups=grps,Sums=sums,MaxCloneSize=maxes );

ggplot( df, aes(x=Groups,y=Diversity)) + 
  geom_boxplot( colour="black" ) +
  geom_jitter( colour="red", height=0, width=0.20 ) +
  theme_pubr() +
  labs( title="MBT06 Shannon Diversity Index" ) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1));

Plot BC size by rank??

l <- list();
for (grp in unique(grps)) {
  
  if (sum( grps == grp ) < 2) next;
  tmp <- as.data.frame(apply( co.2[,cols[ grps == grp ]],2,sort,decreasing=T ));
  colnames(tmp) <- gsub(".+_(R[0-4]+)$","\\1",colnames(tmp));
  tmp2 <- gather( tmp, key="Replicate",value="Fraction" ) %>% 
    filter( Fraction > 0 ) %>% 
    group_by( Replicate ) %>% 
    mutate(Rank=rank(desc(Fraction)));

  l[[grp]] <- tmp2 %>% ggplot( aes( x=Rank,y=Fraction,color=Replicate )) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_point() +
    scale_y_log10( name="Fraction of Population", limits=c(min(tmp2$Fraction),1)) +
    scale_x_log10( name="Clone Rank") +
    labs( title=grp, color="" ) +
    theme_pubr( legend=c(0.8,0.8) );
  
}

Starting populations

Clearly the replicates are reproducible! This starting population is already quite skewed. There are SIX major clones sitting at around 10% each, followed by another FIVE slightly smaller clones sitting closer to 2%, and then the long tail making up the remainder. Thus, it won’t be surprising to see these 11 clones dominate in the end. If they don’t, that might be interesting!

Engraftment

These distributions have spread out from the P0. Come back to make a scatterplot of the P0 samples vs the ENG samples.

Minimally Residual Disease

So this gets interesting. The MRD samples were taken after 18 days of treatment. But two of the MRD_CON samples have become clonal in that time, while the TR and TRA samples have not. I suspect this is speaking more to the growth inhibition due to treatment moreso than a cytotoxic treatment effect. That said, there seems to be a minor reduction in clones in the TR and TRA samples (see lower right of curves).

Recurrences

Even though they’re biological separate, the REC_CON distributions look quite similar to the MRD_CON distributions.

Prepare line plots for MBT06

l2 <- list();
newGrps <- list();
newGrps[["INVITRO"]] <- c("ENG","INVIVO_P0");
newGrps[["MRD"]] <- c("MRD_CON","MRD_TR");
newGrps[["REC"]] <- c("REC_CON","REC_TR");

for (grpL in names(newGrps)) {

  if (sum( grps == grp ) < 2) next;
  tmp <- as.data.frame(apply( co.2[,cols[ grps %in% newGrps[[grpL]]] ],2,sort,decreasing=T ));
  tmp2 <- gather( tmp, key="Replicate",value="Fraction" ) %>% filter( Fraction > 0 ) %>% 
    group_by( Replicate ) %>% mutate(CloneFreq=rank(desc(Fraction)));
  tmp2$Color <- sapply( tmp2$Replicate, function(x) grps[ which( cols == x )]);

  l2[[grpL]] <- tmp2 %>% ggplot( aes( x=log10(Fraction),y=CloneFreq,group=Replicate,color=Color )) +
      geom_line( lwd=1 ) +
      scale_y_log10( name="Clones ≥ \u0192" ) +
      xlim( NA, 0 ) + xlab("Clonal Frequency") + 
      labs( title="MBT06",color="Sample Group" ) +
      theme_pubr( legend=c(0.8,0.8) );
  
}

MBT06 - In Vitro

MBT06 - MRD

What these lineplots seem to show is the following:

MBT06 - Recurrences

How to interpret these curves. It seems like, reproducibly, the Control populations are very much the same. Now, in the TMZ+Radiation tumours:
  • One replicate has become clonal, so looks like an outlier on the plot
  • Interestingly, the other two samples look pretty similar. The “background” population in the upper plateau, the slopes in the steepest part of the curves, the number of dominant clones, and finally the maximum clone size (~10%) all seem very similar between these two replicates. This was perhaps seen more effectively in the lineplots above.

Correlation Matrix of MBT06 Samples

tmp <- as.data.frame(apply( co.2[,cols],2,sort,decreasing=T )) %>% filter( !if_all( where( is.numeric ), ~ .x == 0 ));
cm <- cor( tmp, method="spearman" );
source("~/lib/R/jet.colors.R");
heatmap.2( as.matrix( cm ),scale="none",trace="none",col=jet.colors(128),margins=c(10,10),main="Distribution Correlations",key.title = "",key.xlab = "Pearson Correlation",density.info = "none");
